AKS Authentication & Authorization Summary
1. AKS Private Cluster
API server is private: Only accessible from within the VNet (not public).
Kubeconfig file alone is not enough: You also need network access to the API server.

2. Kubernetes Local Accounts
Local accounts = AKS-managed credentials (admin and user) used for cluster access.
Authentication: Handled by Kubernetes itself (not Azure AD).
Authorization: Controlled by Kubernetes RBAC.

3. Default Local Accounts in AKS
Admin account:
Downloaded with az aks get-credentials --admin
Has full cluster-admin privileges.
User account:
Downloaded with az aks get-credentials
Has full access in default namespace, read-only for cluster-wide resources.
No named RBAC role for "user": Permissions are managed by AKS infrastructure, not a visible role.

4. RBAC and Roles
cluster-admin role: Always present in every Kubernetes cluster, regardless of auth/authz method.
Admin account is bound to cluster-admin by default.
User account is not bound to a named role; permissions are managed internally by AKS.

AKS cluster Authentication and Authorization modes
1) Local accounts with K8s RBAC
AKS manages the user through client certifications & service account tokens. no external users through AD
default users: admin & user. these users can we accessed through
az aks get-credentials --admin - for admin account
az aks get-credentials - for user account
admin account will bind to cluster-admin role in cluster. whereas user account doesn't have associated with role. its permissions are managed internally by azure
admin account has full access, user account has full access on default namespace and read only access on other resources

In other two types of AD authentication, we have the option to enable/disable kubernetes local accounts with checkbox. technically both are same kubernetes local accounts with checkbox checked and using Local accounts with K8s RBAC option.

2) Microsoft Entra ID authentication with Kubernetes RBAC
Only Microsoft Entra ID identities (users, groups, service principals, managed identities) can authenticate to the Kubernetes API server
No local accounts
K8s RBAC assign permissions through role, clusterrole & rolebindings

az aks create \
  --resource-group <RG> \
  --name <AKS_NAME> \
  --enable-aad \
  --aad-admin-group-object-ids <GROUP_OBJECT_ID> \
  --enable-rbac
  
--enable-aad - to use Azure AD authentication
--aad-admin-group-object-ids - group of users to have admin access (full privilege)
--enable-rbac - to use K8s RBAC

