If the user is not part of this assigned AD group, they won't get any permission by default. we have to create role & rolebindings to assign the permissions to users or groups

The above two points are only referring about the authorization part. For authentication, they have to have atleast "Azure Kubernetes Service Cluster User" role assigned on the AKS resource(both AD admin groups assinged and additional manual users).

"Azure Kubernetes Service Cluster User" role allows users to
Download the kubeconfig file for the AKS cluster (using az aks get-credentials or via the Azure Portal).
Access the Kubernetes API server with the credentials from the kubeconfig file

With Kubernetes local accounts, the kubeconfig contains static credentials (certs/tokens), and anyone with the file can use those credentials.
With Azure AD, the kubeconfig is a template for authenticating with Azure AD, not a credential itself.

this means the kubeconfig file generated with AD & K8s RBAC mode is generic template, doesn't contain any credentials. if the user tries to access the api server through this kubeconfig file at that time only it verifies the user by asking to do az login. 

How kubeconfig Works with Azure AD
The kubeconfig file contains a configuration that tells kubectl to use Azure AD for authentication.
When you run a kubectl command for the first time:
If you are not logged in via the Azure CLI, it prompts you to do az login (or a browser-based login).
After you log in, the Azure CLI stores your access token in its own local cache (not in the kubeconfig file).
Subsequent kubectl commands use the cached access token, so you are not prompted to log in again until the token expires or you log out.

Where is authentication info stored?
Access tokens and refresh tokens are stored by the Azure CLI (in your user profile directory) and are not written into the kubeconfig file. (e.g., ~/.azure/accessTokens.json and other files)
The kubeconfig always remains a template pointing to Azure AD as the authentication provider.

access token lifetime is one hr. after that it gets expired. refresh token helps to generate the new access token. refresh token validity is default to 14 days and max 90 days. if the refresh token is not used for a period of time, typically 14 days then it will get expired before 90 days.

If you use 'az aks get-credentials --admin' local accounts, it uses certs and token, its not time limited. doesn't get expired.

