3) Microsoft Entra ID authentication with Azure RBAC
Authentication is done through Azure AD
For authz, it depends on Azure RBAC role assignments
Azure Kubernetes Service RBAC Viewer - Read-only access to resources
Azure Kubernetes Service RBAC Writer - Create, edit, delete workloads
Azure Kubernetes Service RBAC Admin	- Manage workloads and Kubernetes RBAC
Azure Kubernetes Service RBAC Cluster Admin	- Full cluster-admin access

Assign Azure RBAC roles to users/groups/service principals in the Azure Portal or via CLI.
Users log in with Azure AD and run az aks get-credentials to download the kubeconfig (no static credentials).
When running kubectl commands, the AKS API server checks your Azure RBAC role and enforces permissions accordingly

No need to manage Kubernetes RoleBindings/ClusterRoleBindings
Kubernetes RBAC objects are ignored for API access
No need to mention the default AD Admin groups while creating the cluster. 

If local account is enabled, it works regardless of the Azure RBAC access. it still users K8s RBAC for admin access. 
if I run az aks get-credentials --admin - I will get K8s admin access from K8s RBAC (local account)
if I run az aks get-credentials  - I will get authenticated with entra id and it will check against my azure RBAC role for authorization. 

also in K8s RBAC mode, once you downloaded the kubeconfig file it could be used by anyone to access the aks api server. but here in Azure RBAC mode, even if you have the kubeconfig file, you have to be AD user with permission to access the cluster. 

